I just checked out the fvwm mailing list archive (I was unable to
access it recently but it seems to be back now) and I saw a number of
messages about the possibility of extending fvwm with a real extension
language. Some of these posts cited scwm in several ways:

* To suggest that a future version of fvwm should use a non-Scheme
configuration language to avoid redundant development.

* To suggest that maybe scwm should eventually be renamed fvwm3, and
should actually be the future version of fvwm, this being a big win
for everyone involved.

* To mention that the last time this was discussed on fvwm-workers,
the idea of renaming scwm to fvwm3 was opposed.


I would just like to clarify some points about this. I'll be repeating
some of the things I said the last time I posted here, but I hope
people don't mind.


When I originally started the scwm project (this was quite some time
ago), I didn't even consider the possibility that it could actually be
the successor to fvwm. As I saw it, fvwm was a major project that was
in extremely wide use, with relatively closed development, and no one
would have taken me at all seriously if I suddenly posted that I had a
hack to fvwm to replace the configuration

The main reason I chose to base my work on fvwm was because, out of
existing window managers, it was the closest to what I wanted. It
already supported a great deal of configurability.


Now, the last time this possibility was raised, I said that I
personally would not be averse to scwm being fvwm3, but I was doubtful
that this was what the fvwm community really wanted, as fvwm seemed to
have a slightly different set of goals. In particular, I got the
impression that many people in the fvwm community were more interested
in low resource consumption while providing a fair amount of
configurability, than in total configurability. 

However, it seems there are now many people interested in seeing an
extension language in fvwm, possibly including the current maintainer.

As I said the last time this came up, I personally feel honored that
nayone would even think of making scwm into fvwm3. I don't know about
how the other scwm developers feel, but I spoke to Greg Badros, the
other main developer, who is also on this list, at Linux Expo, and he
agreed that a potential merge with another poject would be a good
idea.


I'm in no position to be making a decision about this on behalf of the
fvwm community, but I would like to give a few reasons why I think
guile is a good choice as an extension language. If people think these
reasons are good, then a re-merge, at least in spirit if not
necessarily literally in code, is worth considering.

* Using a made-up ad-hoc language is, I should hope, out of the
question.

* The best way to leverage existing work would probably be to use one
of the big four, Perl, Python, Tcl or Guile.

* Guile provides one of the best C APIs of any extension language. The
only extension language I've heard described as being as easy to
extend in C is Tcl. While interface to the user is important, the
interface to the programmer is important as well.

* Tcl is a bad language in many ways. Having a proper extension
language makes it natural to implement many parts of the window
manager in the language itself. Lacking true data types and any decent
support for modular code design 

* Perl has some controversial syntactic features which would make some
people hate it as much as others would hate Scheme.

* Python has nice syntax and semantics, but is not as popular as perl
or tcl.

* While Guile is currently only truly usable with Scheme, it plans to
support multiple languages in the future. Some people have attacked
this work as vaporware or as "hating other languages so much that they
will be emulated twice as slow". There is some fairness to the first
claim - the work has been on hiatus for some time. But it has recently
been dusted off, and is being worked on again. It is already possible
to use Guile with a C-like syntax, and work on other "real" extension
languages will likely proceed.

The important thing about this feature is not anything like "perl is
useless because we can just translate it into guile" or anything like
that. The important thing is that users will be given a _choice_ of
extension languages to use. I feel this is much better than any single
extension language.

An alternative approach to providing multiple extension languages is
to provide a generic interface int he core and use some kind of module
facility to connect to the individual languages.

I don't think this approach is as good. Integrating the extension
language in the core is important to properly handle the many times
the core needs to call back to user code if you want to properly
provide full programmability. Also, a good extension language provides
a number of useful data types which can be used by the core itself to
improve code organization without reinventing the wheel.


* All the hard work to make fvwm work with Guile is mostly done, in
the form of scwm. What we are doing now is cleaning things up and
adding new features. We're still working on extending the fvwm2 module
support, but it is already good enough to run the pager. A user has
recently mentioned code he has written to extend things even further
and support a number of other modules properly. We also have plans to
write an fvwmrc -> scwmrc conversion script, although this work has
understandably been delayed because scwm has been a pretty fast-moving
target.



There are some caveats however. Although scwm is already used by many
people and is fairly stable for such a relatively immature project, it
is still changing very quickly, and I wouldn't want people to rely on
it without knowing what they were getting into. I fear that a
premature change of name to "fvwm3," before the code is stable enough
to merit the name, would lead to this.

However, if people do want to work together, I think the increased
cooperation would be greatly beneficial.


 - Maciej Stachowiak
