Right.  And we hope to have a one-time translator to help people move
.fvwm2rc's to .scwmrc's to aid in the conversion process.

It's a bit unfortunate (but not unreasonably inaccurate) that scwm is
considered a split from fvwm2 development -- only because the idea of
splitting is looked upon reasonably negatively.  As someone who has
contributed code to fvwm2, I understand about the problems with losing
manpower, but at the time of the "split", fvwm2 development had really
stalled.  We may have made a mistake in not searching for more support
from fvwm-workers earlier.  I say only "may have made a mistake" because 
I'm fairly certain that early periods in a projects life-cycle can
benefit from fewer designers and coders with a more unified vision and
direction.  Maciej (and to a lesser extent I) provided that vision and
direction and have a project that is very usable now, well beyond the
proof of concept stages.

I don't want to have to backpatch fvwm2 with any of the more essential
bug-fixes or features from scwm development, but have tried to be
helpful in the months after the split to the code of mine that has made
it into fvwm2 over the years.  A merge will make that job easier for
me, and will reduce duplicated efforts from groups.

Greg
