Greg Badros <gjb@cs.washington.edu>:
> Merging would be good.  We'd love to hear from fvwm folks about what
> sorts of things they'd like in scwm to make it more to their liking.

I want to say that I wholeheartedly support this plan -- and in fact,
the prospect of an fvwm/scwm makes me much more interested in working
on both.

As a user, I like fvwm2 a lot.  As a developer, I can't help but notice 
that fvwm2's configuration stuff is klugey and rigid and its internals
obscure in the extreme.

As a developer, I like the *concept* of scwm.  It's got to make a better
basis for future evolution than fvwm2.  On the other hand, I'd hate to
lose the fvwm2 look and feel, the interface-engineering tradition that
goes with it.

A window-manager that merged scwm's guts with fvwm2's glory would be ideal.

To those who object to carrying a Scheme interpreter around, I say pooh
on your prejudices.  We have only two choices here; embed a clean interpreter
or embed a lot of ad-hoc code to do logically equivalent things in a
much grubbier way.  This is not a hard decision, especially since a Scheme
interpreter can probably be made smaller than the ad-hoc code!.

What can I do to help this plan along?
-- 
