On Wed, Jul 15, 1998 at 01:10:09PM -0700, Greg Badros wrote:
> But if all you want is static menus, then you probably can be happy with 
> many simpler wm-s than even fvwm2.  Certainly there is overhead in
> running a real languge, but fvwm2 already has a lot of the overhead of a 
> real language while implementing only an underpowered configuration
> dialect that aspires to be a real language.

I can't get the look and feel I want with other WM's.  I'm willing to
bet money that the vast majority of fvwm users use static menus, with
perhaps an M4-generated config based on installed software.  The menus
certainly don't change during operation.

> Active desktop and configurable desktop are very different things.  Scwm 
> is not directly hoping to be an active desktop --- the generality which
> we hope it will have might enable such a thing, but isn't our purpose.

I fail to understand the purpose then, and how it would replace fvwm.

> > Loadable extensions have been a part of FVWM since the days of Rob
> > Nation.  They were part of FVWM's future long before SCWM was even
> > conceived.
> 
> Like what?  I must be missing something -- my fvwm2 sources have
> conditional compilation code everywhere and nothing is dynamically
> loadable.  Perhaps you mean modules?  It's a system that works (we've
> spent some effort to make existing fvwm2 modules work with scwm as a
> migration path) but isn't satisfactory in a lot of ways.

Modules are certainly dynamically loaded and unloaded.  Converting them
to .so files would be interesting, but not necessarily useful.  (The
only real advantage would be lower IPC costs, but, then, you also lose
the simulated multithreading that multiple processes gives you.  A
bigger gain would be made by having libfvwm2 a shared object.)

I'm willing to bet that most users also leave the big-mondo-list of
config options intact except perhaps trimming out XPM's if they still
haven't gotten around to installing libXpm.  The overhead of making XPM
support a .so file would not be worth it.  Nor would 'BorderStyle' or
'Shape' or 'WindowShade' or any of the others.

You seem to be arguing that they SHOULD be .so's, since by 'Loadable
extension' you are stating that modules are not what you mean and the
only other runtime loadable extensions would be .so files.  Again, I
think that far more code would be spent on the overhead of .so's and the
hassles of REALLY ugly code.

For example, WINDOWSHADE is invoked like this a handful of times:
  if(check_allowed_function2(F_MAXIMIZE,tmp_win) == 0
#ifdef WINDOWSHADE
     || (tmp_win->buttons & WSHADE)
#endif
     )
  {

There would be no benefit to allowing the capability to come and go:
you'd lose on 50 line function and a half dozen lines throughout
borders.c, builtins.c, functions.c and resize... but to use a .so would
use more than those half dozen lines to save maybe a couple K of RAM
and hurt portability.

There is a reason such things are in the core code (they are FAR cheaper
to implement there) and there is a reason they are #ifdef'able (some
people may not have the capability to use Xpm's or Shape extensions
or just REALLY hate any change in code size and #ifdef's are free to
execute and cost virtually nothing to compile).

Again, perhaps you don't mean 'shared objects' by terms like 'loadable
extensions' and 'dynamically loadable'.  You have stated that despite
Modules being loadable and extending and being dynamically loadable that
you don't mean them.  The only thing I think you could mean would be
shared objects.

> In any case, we don't claim to be inventing the idea of loadable
> extensions to a wm, only hoping to implement them nicely enough the we
> satisfy both the power hungry users and those wanting a more lean wm.

Then what are the goals of scwm and why should it replace fvwm?  The
original post was a slightly more polite version of "Fwvm2 is dead,
quit using it or even working on future versions of Fvwm2:  work on my
code and we'll call it Fvwm3.  Be assimilated or die."

The day that fvwm requires an internal interpreted language is the day I
stop upgrading it.

