Tools exist to manage the complexity of dynamically loadable code in a
cross-platform way.  Once a framework is in place, having dynamically
loaded primitives is not a big problem.  It's not so much that, e.g.,
the window shading code should come and go, but more that if you don't
use window shading, you shouldn't pay for that code sitting around in
your process image anyway.  There's also an extensibility argument--
module communicate through a thin straw unsuitable for many kinds of
extensions like window decoration primitives.

