On Wed, Jul 15, 1998 at 02:15:43PM -0700, Greg Badros wrote:
> brian moore <bem@cmc.net> writes:
> 
> > I can't get the look and feel I want with other WM's.  I'm willing to
> > bet money that the vast majority of fvwm users use static menus, with
> > perhaps an M4-generated config based on installed software.  The menus
> > certainly don't change during operation.
> 
> But they should be able to change.  Why should you have to restart your
> wm when you install a new application that you want accessible via a wm
> "Applications" menus.

Then use FvwmPipe and talk to it through a pipe.  I certainly don't want
it doing something like add_menu(`find / -type f -perm 001`) every time
I pull down a menu.  Or FvwmTalk.  There are lots of ways to add menu
items without restarting Fvwm2 or even putting them in a config file.
And I sure as hell don't want application software deciding that 'make
install' means to go fuck with my window manager.  Any software that
does that will be rm'd.

> Tools exist to manage the complexity of dynamically loadable code in a
> cross-platform way.  Once a framework is in place, having dynamically
> loaded primitives is not a big problem.  It's not so much that, e.g.,
> the window shading code should come and go, but more that if you don't
> use window shading, you shouldn't pay for that code sitting around in
> your process image anyway.  There's also an extensibility argument--
> module communicate through a thin straw unsuitable for many kinds of
> extensions like window decoration primitives.

Are you talking about modules or about core code?  Windowshade, the
example cited, is CORE code.  There isn't a huge communications overhead
in something that is in, appropriately enough, 'builtins.c'.  Your last
sentence, then is yet another red herring.  If you don't use
Windowshades, the calls will STILL have to be made to see if the bits
are set because the objecting was that they were ifdef'd.  The only
'savings' for real would be the 50 lines or so of the actual function in
builtins.c.

Is that worth it?  You seem to think so, as so far the only argument you
have presented is that unloading and loading single functions like
WindowShade should be done with .so's.  Does it really take linking with
a 370k library to unload and load a 50 line function?

> FAR cheaper?  What dynamic linking system are you using?  Dynamically
> loaded code is pretty damn lightweight, and can be done cleanly and
> unobtrusively to the rest of the system.

Subroutine calls to fpic'd functions are cheaper than an || to a bit?
(Never mind that the subroutine call will do the exact same || to a bit
and that in the process will clean your instruction prefetch cache
and other fun.)

> > > In any case, we don't claim to be inventing the idea of loadable
> > > extensions to a wm, only hoping to implement them nicely enough the we
> > > satisfy both the power hungry users and those wanting a more lean wm.
> > 
> > Then what are the goals of scwm and why should it replace fvwm?  The
> > original post was a slightly more polite version of "Fwvm2 is dead,
> > quit using it or even working on future versions of Fvwm2:  work on my
> > code and we'll call it Fvwm3.  Be assimilated or die."
> 
> :-)

You haven't answered the question: What are the goals of scwm and why
should it replace (not peaceful coexistence: you argued for replacement
and seem to have brought your own cheering squad along with you) Fvwm?

> So perhaps scwm isn't for you, but it sounds like you're happy with
> fvwm2 the way it is and that's fine.  I'm pretty sure that the generic
> plans for fvwm2.3 would've left your needs behind, too, and that's fine,
> too.  Along the lines of minimalistic wm with static configurations, the
> horse is dead and has been beaten for quite a while now.  For those who
> want or need something more, perhaps scwm is the right direction.

If you succeed in using the Fvwm name, I will be glad to provide
facilities and time for a fork for the people who wish to continue.

Again, mail -either- the list or me.  I really don't need two copies of
every piece of mail.

-- 
