brian moore <bem@cmc.net> writes:

<snip>

> Are you talking about modules or about core code?  Windowshade, the
> example cited, is CORE code.  There isn't a huge communications overhead
> in something that is in, appropriately enough, 'builtins.c'.  Your last
> sentence, then is yet another red herring.  If you don't use
> Windowshades, the calls will STILL have to be made to see if the bits
> are set because the objecting was that they were ifdef'd.  The only
> 'savings' for real would be the 50 lines or so of the actual function in
> builtins.c.

Your example is bogus.  We wouldn't have a function call to do that
test, the dynamically loaded code would be just the primitives to manage 
the shading.   The window shading feature is most definitely not core
code -- if I don't use it, I don't want it loaded if it's easy to avoid
loading.  But this is way off topic, scwm's main contribution isn't
dynamically loaded code (we don't use it at all aggressively yet)--
those remarks were to pacify people concerned about code bloat of
primitives they don't care about.

> You haven't answered the question: What are the goals of scwm and why
> should it replace (not peaceful coexistence: you argued for replacement

<snip>

We are not arguing for replacement.  Fvwm1 and fvwm2 have their place
and will remain.  We are simply suggesting that the future direction for 
the scwm coincides with some expressed interest in future direction for
fvwm2, and that perhaps scwm is far enough along in that direction that
it makes more sense for interested developers of fvwm2 to join forces
with scwm developers.  Fvwm2 could continue to develop and have bug
fixes, but replacing its configuration language has been done, and done
well IMHO by the scwm-team many months ago.

> > So perhaps scwm isn't for you, but it sounds like you're happy with
> > fvwm2 the way it is and that's fine.  I'm pretty sure that the generic
> > plans for fvwm2.3 would've left your needs behind, too, and that's fine,
> > too.  Along the lines of minimalistic wm with static configurations, the
> > horse is dead and has been beaten for quite a while now.  For those who
> > want or need something more, perhaps scwm is the right direction.
> 
> If you succeed in using the Fvwm name, I will be glad to provide
> facilities and time for a fork for the people who wish to continue.

We have no need to use the fvwm name; scwm is a perfectly good name.  I
only wish to merge the efforts related to dynamic configurability, and
get more developers behind scwm.  Duplicated efforts serve no one well,
and I honestly believe scwm is far better positioned to be the future of 
fvwm2 users wanting more than fvwm2 is.  Those that don't need the
power/flexibility can stay behind as they did with fvwm1.  Scwm isn't
for everyone, but it probably is for those crying out for a better
language with fvwm2.

Greg
