During the last go-around on this, the "add one million bytes" issue
seemed like a show-stopper to me.

I did take the time to download Scwm and was impressed by how clean
the config files looked when XEmacs could fully understand them and
highlight them accordingly.

However  as I looked through the  config files  is  wasn't clear to me
what I would do with this new, more flexible language.  As I use fvwm2
now, I don't  use FvwmCpp, FvwmM4, or  FvwmPipe.  I support fvwm2  for
over 20 users,  and none of  them report the  need  for a more  robust
config language either.

Along the  same line, as we  get fvwm2 users  problem reports, I don't
recall hearing problems that made me think, "if  only fvwm2 had a more
robust configuration language...".

I have  a hint what  most users want  is a GUI of  some sort that will
magically  configure menus for new remote  systems to start Xterms on,
and the like.  It isn't clear to me that cleaning up the configuration
language will make fvwm2 more amenable to GUI configuration.

I  do make  extensive  use  of  fvwm2  macros.  Even  though the macro
facility is primitive, it hasn't let me down yet.

If, through some  magic,  all fvwm2 development  ground to  a halt, my
first inclination  would be to say fvwm2  is good enough.  To convince
me to switch I would need:

  a foolproof way to convert .fvwm2rc files to Scwm config files (Note
that the current fvwm1 to fvwm2 conversion tool is far from foolproof)

  a fully documented Scwm

  all current fvwm2 modules working

  something compelling in Scwm that I can't get from fvwm2

