Late response...

mstachow> I saw a number of messages about the possibility of
mstachow> extending fvwm with a real extension language. Some of these
mstachow> posts cited scwm in several ways:

If the fvwm employs another language as the configulation language, I
think it is not fvwm. We should not forget that why fvwm throw away
the configulation language which twm uses, and employs cpp/m4 as
higher level description language. Again, we should not forget the
great design policy of fvwm.

***

mstachow> * To suggest that a future version of fvwm should use a
mstachow> non-Scheme configuration language to avoid redundant
mstachow> development.

Yes, that's right, and it should be avoided. fvwm configulation
language is just like the one of sendmail; higher (and more human
friendly) language is not provided core-part of program. fvwm
configulation description language is just like x86 assemble language; 
we can use other higher level language as we like.

mstachow> * To suggest that maybe scwm should eventually be renamed
mstachow> fvwm3, and should actually be the future version of fvwm,
mstachow> this being a big win for everyone involved.

Why? Scwm should have its own success story 'cause it is not fvwm.

mstachow> * To mention that the last time this was discussed on fvwm-workers,
mstachow> the idea of renaming scwm to fvwm3 was opposed.

Last time we do the right decision. It comes from very obvious and
very simple reason, "scwm is not fvwm."

***

Why you want to "merge" the fvwm and scwm? If scwm is great, fvwm will 
be died by itself. You don't worry about that :-)

-- -
Makoto `MAR' MATSUSHITA
