Whew, it's a good thing you're stepping back into the discussion since
folks are getting pretty ornery on this topic. My sense is that
consensus *can't* be found here, since it looks like the issue is
devolving into a question of religion.

But it seems to me it's about time some folks got alienated for good
though... Look, I don't see that it's feasible to keep fvwm a
RAM-consumption mouse *and* provide a well-designed option for a
turing-complete configuration language. I *could* see returning to the
earlier notion of extending the modules interface so an interpreter
could be made sufficiently functional as a module, but I don't think
*anyone* will be happy with that... No one will really grumble too
loudly, but no one will be happy either, I suspect. I really don't see
a good way to build a consensus here and a decision has to be made
here.

As far as fvwm's design and architecture, I haven't got a lot to say
since I'm far too unskilled to offer an intelligent opinion. But I am
curious to know:

    When we talk about embedding an interpreter in fvwm which is
    managing the configuration, are we saying that the same language
    will *also* provide the basis for writing extension modules? I.e.,
    will FvwmPager, for example, be entirely writable and runnable
    from what essentially used to be .fvwm2rc?
    
    I'm assuming that an implicit assumption of those who resist an
    embedded interpreter is that similar functionality could be done
    as a module, if the module interface were expanded/improved. What
    kind of impact would such an expansion/improvement have on fvwm's
    core's size? I don't expect anyone's saying that adding a proper
    interpreter *somewhere* is a Bad Thing, people just don't want it
    as the single-available option in the core...

I *will* comment that as a *non*-programmer, setting up my fvwm2 has
really seemed a lot like programming at times. *Especially* when
working with my modules configurations. It becomes the *most*
pronounced when I start thinking a cute little FvwmForm could solve a
little problem for me. FvwmForm basically exposes the XForm toolkit to
scripting through Fvwm's configuration language... This is an oddity
and really makes the division between programmable extension language
and configuration language blur and make me go dizzy...

I suppose that if one has to choose one of the extreme options (since
I don't expect any compromise is feasible) it's important to finally
decide what's fvwm's design principle. At heart, this discussion, it
seems to me, is about the question, "Is FVWM 1) a small, fast wm
foremost or 2) ultimately, a highly-configurable wm?" The trouble is
that proponents for each side see that there's already something quite
good at each end: twm on the one hand; scwm on the other...

Just some thoughts from a (not completely) satisfied fvwm2 user.
