I'm inclined to believe it when I see it.
So far we are being told that Scwm is at least 1 meg larger than fvwm2.

Here's whats I found on the TO-DO list that I  think is related to the
config language:

  - Access to certain window attribs from .fvwm2rc funcs, and
    simple if/else capabilities (or perhaps a module to do so)??
  - Simple static variables for .fvwm2rc functions (for toggles, etc)??
  - Add $d variable for functions to get desktop number?

Is this 1 meg of code?

I   think Greg has    said as  much.  We   need  to understand  what a
full-blown configuration language is going  to do for fvwm2 before  we
pay the price.

It seems to  me, if we are talking  about a 20% overhead increase, the
average end user should see some benefit.   Any more than that, should
come with a dramatic improvement.

Don't forget my prior point  about the conversion  script.  I have  my
doubts that  a fully  functional fvwm2 to  Scwm converter  is going to
appear.

As far as Brady's comment about the  huge segment of users watching in
quiet horror, don't forget this is the  workers list.  Most users have
no cause to be on any fvwm list, let alone the workers list.

I don't think my reaction is quiet horror, but I am concerned.  I very
much   appreciate Gregs  prior   contributions, and I  try   not to be
negative about new  ideas,  but I think  Scwm  is ahead of   its time.
Someday we may look back and wonder why we had dozens of configuration
languages, but that seems to be years off.

If   XEmacs,  Netscape and Scwm   were  using  the  same configuration
language from a  common  shared library,  that  would be a   different
story.   We just haven't arrived  in that particular  heaven yet.  Nor
does it seem to be on the horizon.

I think Scwm is a very interesting project. For  now, I am looking for
the fvwm2 project stay on track and serve its user base.

