This is a really bad way to go. Hacking on features to the language
one at a time will result in a total mess, and will end up bloating
the code more, ultimately, then adding a real language will. The other
problem is that such simple mechanisms will severely limit what kind
of programmability a user can use in his code, because the interpreter
will be really slow unless you take great pains to design it
well. Some timing tests of SCM, the Scheme interpreter Guile is based
on, indicate that it beats the pants off _any_ other interpreted
language, and beats most byte-compilers except severely statically
typed stuff like Java. Guile has lost a bit of that speed, but Aubrey
Jaffer, the author of SCM, has offered to do a lot of speed
optimization on Guile once the basic code stabilizes enough. This is
important because it allows you to safely write code in the extension
language that does complex things, and yet still runs reasonably fast.

> 
> Is this 1 meg of code?

I have to correct a misconception here, scwm does not have 1 meg more
of _code_, it is one meg more of _memory usage_, due to the large
amount of stuff libguile puts on the heap. And my statement about this
was acutally incorrect. I get RSS of 1.7M with a simple setup now, as
opposed to 1.1M with fvwm2 and this is still while we are in feature
explosion stage, with a _lot_ of subsequent trimming to happen later.

The scwm _code_ itself is actually smaller on disk than the current
size of the fvwm binary (and that's not even counting the fvwm modules
you can get the effect of using it, without having to run them) if you
don't count the large amounts of extra functionality (synthetic key
and mouse presses, animated moves and window shades, user-levele X
Property handling, and many others) which are orthogonal to the
configurability support itself, and which will go into dynamically
loadable shared modules pretty soon.

> 
