I think it is fewer years off than you may think. This is an attempt
to plan for the future early.

> If   XEmacs,  Netscape and Scwm   were  using  the  same configuration
> language from a  common  shared library,  that  would be a   different
> story.   We just haven't arrived  in that particular  heaven yet.  Nor
> does it seem to be on the horizon.
> 

Both Emacs and thus presumably XEmacs will be using Guile in the
future. So will gdb, and probably other FSF-maintained apps as
well. Netscape probably will stick with JavaScript, I'd imagine.

> I think Scwm is a very interesting project. For  now, I am looking for
> the fvwm2 project stay on track and serve its user base.
> 

I don't think anyone is even suggesting otherwise. There is no
question that Scwm is not yet fully end user ready. I think the 0.x
version number makes clear that, although it may be useful to many
people, it is primarily a developer/hacker release for people who
really like playing with their window managers. And certainly, the
concerns about the current memory usage, and the current lack of an rc
file translator, are very valid.

The question is really what should happen when the fvwm2 series
stabilizes. What comes in the next developer series? A number of
people have suggested configuration languages like python, perl or
tcl. Some have even suggested scheme, and as a result, Scwm was
mentioned. I suggest that to avoid duplicating work, if that vision is
really the future of fvwm.

