>>>>> "BM" == Brady Montz <bradym@cs.arizona.edu> writes:

BM> First comment: this discussion seems to be humming along
BM> nicely.

I will remind everyone to please make sure that <mstachow@mit.edu> gets a
copy; as a (the?) primary scwm author who is not a member of fvwm-workers,
he needs to see this discussion.

BM> However, my private feelings in support of (a) adding an extension
BM> language to fvwm, (b) that this language be scheme, and (c) rewriting
BM> large chunks of fvwm are merely my feelings.

I've seen some good arguments as to why it won't work to have the
configuration language be a module.  I've yet to see mention of the idea of
having more than one core (being the configuration language plus builtins)
and have everything else be modular (or in a shared library).  (In other
words, two essentially different window managers sharing a whole lot of
code.)

In the end, I'm really partial to saying that fvwm3 will be new and
different, while fvwm2 will continue to be supported in perpetuity.  That
ensures that "fvwm" (as a project) will still go somewhere, while fvwm2
stays small (because you can tell people to just use fvwm3 if they want
some particular feature).

I think, though, that for anything to be called fvwm3, it has to at least
try to stay true to what fvwm has always stood for.  It needs to be
functional (no argument about scwm here) and frugal.  Fortunately frugality
is relative; making it "small" should always be a goal, even if that means
telling people not to use some available features to save space.  It
doesn't have to be within some percentage of fvwm2's (or 1's) size, because
computers really have advanced and memory doesn't mean quite what it used
to.

BM> Fvwm in its current form will not last.

I agree.  It is being pulled in (at least) two directions and it's
impossible for a maintainer to just split the difference.  That's why
development usually splits in the first place.  (Well, that and stagnation,
but we seem to have fixed that lately.)  But instead of a complete split, I
think it would be worthwhile to have two programs, one oriented towards
features and another oriented towards size, both sharing as much code and
programming effort as possible.

BM> 2. Find a way to balance the needs of the minimalists and
BM> maximalists. I don't personally know of a program which has truly done
BM> this (although vim actually has done a good job, since I can turn off
BM> everything I don't want, so I still like vim - no hard feelings), but
BM> it can probably be done "good enough." I suspect this will involve
BM> taking large portions of scwm, but being able to compile both fvwm and
BM> fvwm-lite. People supporting this have to demonstrate that it can be
BM> done.

Can it be done?  I don't know.  We'd have to start by comparing
functionality and feature sets and see what can be put into libraries that
can be used by two different cores.  It is not a simple task.  (Both scwm
and fvwm would be better for it if it were done, though, even if nobody was
talking about a merge.)

