Brady Montz <bradym@cs.arizona.edu>:
>2. Find a way to balance the needs of the minimalists and maximalists. I don't
>   personally know of a program which has truly done this (although vim
>   actually has done a good job, since I can turn off everything I don't want,
>   so I still like vim - no hard feelings), but it can probably be done "good
>   enough." I suspect this will involve taking large portions of scwm, but
>   being able to compile both fvwm and fvwm-lite. People supporting this have
>   to demonstrate that it can be done.
>
> I think that #2 may be the way to go.

I think so, too.  As a person who's not in either the fvwm or scwm camps,
but who's been around the track a few times, I may have a strategy to suggest
for accomplishing it.  It'll take a little give and goodwill on both sides.

I can see a merge working given three commitments:

1. The scwm people must provide a fully capable .fvwm2rc-to-.scwmrc
   translator.

2. Scwm must support all existing fvwm2 modules.

3. The fvwm people must accept that for the first few releases (until
   guile gets space-tuned), the scwm/fvwm3 code may have a bigger footprint
   than the existing fvwm2.  

In other words: if the scwm people will live with a requirement that
scwm be painlessly upward-compatible with fvwm2, and the fvwm2 people
will cut them *temporary* slack on the footprint issue, we can all
make this work.

There's a reason I emphasize `temporary'.  We're talking about replacing
the ad-hoc config code with Guile.  A key advantage of this is that it
would allow fvwm to leverage lots more brains than just the fvwm workers.
Better dynamic-loading and modularization for Guile is critical-path
for lots of projects besides ours.  It's much more likely that Guile 
will improve dramatically than that we will ever get motivated enough to
clean up the ad-hoc cruft in fvwm2's present guts.

Eventually, here's what I hope we can all agree to deliver:  a version of
scwm that, when called through a link named fvwm2, reads .fvwm2rc,
translates it on the fly to Guile, and runs just like fvwm2 (modulo
bug fixes).

The program used for .fvwm2rc-to-Guile translation should, of course,
be available standalone for people who want to go pure Guile right away.
