On Thu, Jul 16, 1998 at 07:21:35PM -0400, Eric S. Raymond wrote:
> brian moore <bem@cmc.net>:
> > Again, it is incredibly rude and arrogant for you and Maciej to show up
> > on this list with the attitude of zealots trying to convert the masses.
> 
> Cool your jets, dude.  You're being a lot ruder right now than either 
> of those two have been.  And guess which one of the three of you sounds
> like a zealot?

I'm not 'dude'.

> If you keep this up, "small-is-beautiful" will lose a credible
> defender, which would be a shame.  Somebody's got to keep Greg and
> Maciej on their toes about the economy and footprint issues.  I was
> expecting it would be you, but you're sabotaging your own arguments
> rather effectively by flaming and making these peevish threats to 
> start a hostile fork.

I won't have to keep them on their toes because they have yet to offer a
compelling reason to bloat the code.  It's interesting to hear someone
that has supposedly pondered the nature of open source criticizing
forks.  When program development doesn't meet the needs of a
significant number of users, it is time to fork.  I believe that
requiring guile will not meet their needs and that users will stick
with an unsupported and undeveloped product instead of "upgrading".

I believe they deserve better than that.

You think it's "peevish" to not want to follow the direction of the
current maintainer of code?  Perhaps you should add that wisdom to your
essays.  "People who don't like the way code is going dare not try to
take it in a different direction."  It will show a whole new side of
you since it contradicts much of what you have written before.

> Fetchmail doesn't have Guile because fetchmail doesn't need Guile.  As
> presently designed, fetchmail is just a keep-it-simple-stupid mail
> transport agent.

And why would FVWM benefit from Guile?  I have asked that repeatedly and
gotten silly answers.  Since you jumped right on the boat stating it
would be good, please explain what functionality would be added.

Not the general code cleanup that has been done and is sorely needed in
Fvwm, but the linking of Guile (or, for that matter, requiring any
language to be built into the core).

> If fetchmail were going to do content-based filtering or something
> else that suggested it needed a Turing-complete language, I'd bolt
> Guile onto fetchmail in about a nanosecond.

Would you mandate it?  If you did, you can bet people would fork it.
("Procmail does enough, why do I need this?")

> When you get down to it, POP and IMAP just aren't very complicated.
> Because this is true, fetchmail can be both right and *simple*.  The
> semantic domain of window-manager configurations, OTOH, is much, much
> richer; enough so to suggest such a language.

And a WM isn't that complicated.  Some very respectible WM's exist that
have no such language.  WindowMaker, AfterStep, Enlightenment -- none of
which require such a language.

> BTW, if you'd like to join fetchmail-friends and trash my design, feel free.
> I'm sure the response from the regulars there would be, hm, well,
> "entertaining" is the word that occurred to me second.

I didn't trash their design: I asked what functionality it would add and
was treated with 'features' like listing all the screen savers for
xlock, moving Netscape windows, and a supposedly smaller footprint. 
The first two are 'features' that are not worth the added size of the
program (and I've seen the first implemented with a shell script and
the second with FvwmScript), and the smaller footprint isn't true.

So precisely, why should I accept more complexity in the program
(certainly adding an interpreter is going to add complexity) instead of
just cleaning up the existing code?

Or is it somehow wrong to actually ask "WHY" before a feature is thrown
in now?

