On 16-Jul-98 Greg Badros wrote:

> ...nifty things people have done with Scwm -- the most recent that jumps
> to mind is using our window-style's other-proc feature to customize the
> placement of windows that meet a specific criteria -- e.g., making netscape's
> popup windows go to a specific place...

        I've not had time to look into other-proc, but this funcionality has
been available to Fvwm2 users for nearly a year with my StartsOnPage patch.
It's been floating around in Limbo, because Chuck didn't have the time to work
it into a release, but a number of users are quite addicted to the feature.


        But I digress....

        My main reservation about a merger of Scwm and Fvwm is the same
one voiced by Chuck in his parting comments. I think there's a need
for a WM with the capabilities of Fvwm that is stand-alone, not
requiring other large packages to be installed. (I think the cross-
package dependencies are more the issue than the memory/disk footprint.)

        I have both Fvwm and Scwm installed on my personal machine at
home - indeed, I have most of the WM's currently in popular use, and
actually use most of them from time to time - but I might not have
the option of installing Scwm, Guile, et. al. on certain machines at
work, whereas the current Fvwm would be no problem. (If this scenario
sounds familiar to anyone, please speak up!)

        From my own experience, I'd have to agree with Dan's 
observation: I've not felt the need for a "more powerful" configuration
language. However, to play devil's advocate for a moment, I'll concede
a major benefit to be derived from plugging in a "standard" language -
consistency. This is because the existing configuration "language" is 
subject to the whims/inexperience/personality-quirks/whatever of 
whoever is patching in a new primitive when it comes to syntax and 
parsing. This could definitely stand improving.

        I think that the only way a merger can satisfy the needs of
both the self-contained and the extensible-WM camps is with a 
restructuring of the WM into a configuration layer and a core layer,
such that the configuration layer is effectively a plug-in, and does
*not* creep into the core layer. A rigorous layer separation with 
well-defined interface points should allow the core layer to serve 
as a common WM-engine - almost like a toolkit, actually - that could
serve to build both an Scwm and a  conventional guileless Fvwm (with
its existing, though doubtless much-modified, config layer). 

        I know you're going to object that there are certain "core" 
functions that could be better handled in Scheme - and you're probably 
right, but we might want to consider whether that implies that they 
shouldn't really be considered part of the core layer. Also, I don't
suggest that it should be illegal to override a core primitive function
with an extension ("hey, override that core method, Greg, the original 
code really sucks!").

        I may be pipe-dreaming - the two code bases may already have
diverged far enough that this approach is no longer practical - I 
haven't had time to look over the Scwm code in enough detail to judge.
Or, there may not be enough people who agree with this idea. But it'd
sure be nice to have a common base so that both groups wouldn't 
constantly need to be reinventing the others' wheels - like the Great
Style Flag Rewrite, which has long since been done for Scwm.

        Now...time to wade through today's mail and see where this 
thread's gone while I was at work.


 
