Read more carefully next time.  You appear to have oversimplified my
analysis to the point of parody.

>                     Since you jumped right on the boat stating it
> would be good, please explain what functionality would be added.

That's not my argument.  I think it sounds like a good idea because I
think the existing configuration language is ugly, ad-hoc, and
un-extensible.  As it is, I don't want to touch it.  But I don't have
a specific wish-list of added functions, just a design sense that the
existing language is far too impoverished to really capture the
configuration domain.

> Not the general code cleanup that has been done and is sorely needed in
> Fvwm, but the linking of Guile (or, for that matter, requiring any
> language to be built into the core).

OK.  You concede that we need "code cleanup".  Why resist embedding
Guile as a tactic for actually accomplishing this?  There is after all
evidence (in the form of scwm itself, 6K smaller) that the tactic works.

> > If fetchmail were going to do content-based filtering or something
> > else that suggested it needed a Turing-complete language, I'd bolt
> > Guile onto fetchmail in about a nanosecond.
> 
> Would you mandate it?  If you did, you can bet people would fork it.
> ("Procmail does enough, why do I need this?")

Nope.  I'd probably make Guile and filtering a build-time option.  Not
because I'd fear a fork, but simply for parsimony's sake.
 
> > When you get down to it, POP and IMAP just aren't very complicated.
> > Because this is true, fetchmail can be both right and *simple*.  The
> > semantic domain of window-manager configurations, OTOH, is much, much
> > richer; enough so to suggest such a language.
> 
> And a WM isn't that complicated.  Some very respectible WM's exist that
> have no such language.  WindowMaker, AfterStep, Enlightenment -- none of
> which require such a language.

And, IIRC, all of these are "one-true-way" WMs designed to enforce a
single theory of interface-gesture design.  Not analogous to fvwm2 at
all.

> So precisely, why should I accept more complexity in the program
> (certainly adding an interpreter is going to add complexity) instead of
> just cleaning up the existing code?

I think your premise is wrong and Greg Badros is clearly right about
this issue, if perhaps vulnerable on others.  Embedding Guile will actually
*lower* total complexity by banishing the nasty ad-hoc code that gives
rise to so much of it.

Yesterday I believed this on general design-engineering grounds.  Today
I believe it because I've dipped into the code and configs enough to
see that it's specifically true of scwm.

You aren't going to win the total-complexity argument, because you're
simply wrong there.  You might win the big-footprint, compatibility,
or stability arguments.  I suggest you focus on those.
