On Thu, Jul 16, 1998 at 05:58:50PM -0400, Eli Burke wrote:
> As another outsiding tossing in commentary, I just want to point out
> that you are doing nothing to help your cause, which seems to be
> approximately: "Don't let anyone change fvwm2 any!"

No, it's Please Back Things Up With Accurate Data.

I've already stated (in <19980715121948.J20760@cmc.net>):
| I'm not.... I don't mind greatly if the config file format changes: I
| don't want my WM to have to be running an interpreter all the time.
|
| I don't think it's a Good Thing to require a Scheme (or Perl or Tcl or
| Python or Java or COBOL, for that matter) interpreter be running in
| order to have static menus.
|
| If the push is to have an interface that will -allow- Scheme, that would
| be okay, but that's not what scwm is about.

I dealt with the Fvwm1.24->2.0 changes long ago.  Change isn't a big
deal.  MANDATING that an interpreter be built into the WM (or anything:
I would be pissed at the Apache Group if they made mod_perl mandatory
and I'm not thrilled that the default vim build will link perl if it
finds it without asking -- I don't use vim, though, so have only griped
about it a couple times) is uneeded.

I have asked for just why this code is needed and been given answers
like "it's not really that much code, and besides it's really SMALLER
now, not bigger!" [which is demonstrably false] or "you could do really
vital things like have a menu item with all of xlock's modes!".

Perhaps you find that a compelling argument to require an extra meg of
RAM, an alpha-level library and all else that goes with it into
something as critical as your window manager.  I don't.

> Your arguements are largely unrelated to the issues at hand, like this one:

It's unrelated that my WM will need libtermcap to run?  Why would it
need it?  Let's just link to everything, whether we need it or not, eh?

> > Termcap??  WTF?
> 	[snip]
> > libs.  (At least termcap is almost always loaded by something else.)
> 	[gee.. a non-arguement per your own comment]

No, it's -20 points for requiring a pointless library, reduced to -19
since at least there's reasonable odds that another application has it
in RAM already.

> > It's the same size plus a 370k library.
> 
> 	What machine are you using that 370k is such an issue? An Ultrix
> box? An i486 with 16M of RAM? For our edification, please tell us what
> system you are running, and what it is that you want out of fvwm2/beyond. 
> If you are perfectly happy with your current build, (or perhaps your build 
> + some patches that could be integrated) then lets hear it. If you will be 
> unhappy if *any* more features are added, say so. 

Sun3's with 16-20M of RAM, SS2's with 64M, and a couple Pentiums with
32-64M.  scwm was noticably slower on them when I tried it in May.  (I
didn't bother trying it on the Sun3's.)

> 	Once you have listed all the features that you, as the de facto
> governing party, deem acceptable, explain your reasoning. If memory size
> is the overriding goal, explain why, and why fvwm1/fvwm2-current aren't
> good enough to stick with while we move to the next century. 

All I ask is that before the RAM footprint is increased by 30%-50% and
performance noticeably affected that some compelling need is shown: 
some real advantage.  Having a pulldown menu with 80 some modes of xlock
ain't it.  Nor is making Netscape's menus start in a fixed location.
Yet those are the reasons given.

> 	It just sounds to me like you have configured yourself the way 
> you like, and can't bear the thought of having to ever change your 
> configuration. In that case, it is your perogative to stick with your
> the version (which is fairly stable) and unsubscribe to this list.

Nonsense: I change my configs all the time.  I have built every release
of fvwm2 since 2.0.9, I believe, and have changed my config to deal with
the things that broke at every version.

> 	If this isn't the case, stop harping on the same subject 
> (370k 370k 370k 370k!!!! Aiiigh!) and be constructive. We already know
> full well that you don't want anything to do with scheme. Well, Brady
> put foward several possible options; why don't you comment on those
> for a change.

I have asked for a REASON for this change.  That's hardly non
constructive.  Or is the current trend in development "let's throw all
the crap in we can because some year it may be useful"?   This is not a
minor change: for perspective, it is tripling the effective code size by
linking a library that is twice the size of fvwm2.  So far, there has
been only some pretty silly reasons for such a thing.

If we were talking "lookie, a silly feature that adds 50 lines!" and a
bunch of people thought, "it's stupid, only you will want it", it
could be ifdef'd out.  There is no choice with scwm.  You either load
an extra 370k (again, twice the size of fvwm2:  the number -is-
relevant, in that if fvwm2 were 50M we wouldn't blink at 370k) or you
don't use it.  I wouldn't object to even the stupidest features ("I want
all my menus to print upside down!") being in the distribution as long
as they were trivial to disable for people who didn't want them.  If it
were an .fvwmrc file option ('GoofyMenus On') I wouldn't care much if it
were in the default build: it's only 50 lines, after all, not twice the
size of everything else.

Brady's comments in <t8btqp1zgf.fsf@helvetica.cs.arizona.edu> are on the
mark for the most part.  I think his unnumbered item in the last
paragraph would actually work the best in the long run if it could be
pulled off: not so much with scwm, but with scwm, afterstep, the
abandoned/adopted fvwm95, etc.  It is an incredible waste that AfterStep
(which is actually not a bad WM, though I dislike it's configuration
methods) and others have forked off instead of working on the core and
perhaps enhancing the module API to do what they need.  If he could
bring them back into the fold and enhance the API for modules (or
perhaps as compile/link time modules like Apache modules for better
execution times, or as the same thing but dl'ing like Apache 1.3 for
flexibility) that would be a Good Thing for all the spawns of fvwm.
(Hell, FvwmWharf is stolen from AfterStep and I use it all the time.)

I said as much a couple months ago on the users fvwm list when I asked
what exactly it was missing from the module API that forbade making
'FvwmPerl', 'FvwmPython' and a non-existant Scheme module do
everything that people wanted.  See <19980504151535.D32688@cmc.net>
posted on May 4th.  No direct answers as to what was missing -- just a
long "I want HTML", "I want Scheme", etc thread about what language it
should be, not why it could be less specific.  I asked how embedding
TCL would add anything in <19980429130655.G8755@cmc.net> on April 29th
(no answer).

Again, I have no objection to having hooks for generic module support of
ANY language: if people want to build COBOL into their desktop, that's
fine by me.  I dislike mandating Thou Shalt Link Guile With Thine
Window Manager for such dubious benefits as xlock-menus and fixing
programs that refuse to honor geometry specifications.

