On Thu, Jul 16, 1998 at 08:46:38PM -0400, Eric S. Raymond wrote:
> Read more carefully next time.  You appear to have oversimplified my
> analysis to the point of parody.

Perhaps you should write more clearly then.

You argue that it is 'peevish' to hold your ground on whether or not a
feature should be installed.  I maintain that is the nature of Open
Source, whether it be Linus insisting that certain code won't make it
into the kernel or whether it is the Apache group deciding that NCSA
wouldn't do what they wanted and weren't taking patches so they'd do it
themselves.

Linus has a lot of charisma and so far has not had a serious challenge
to his decisions.  Some year, no doubt, he will, and there will be a
fork, just as the BSD's seem to fork every two years.

> >                     Since you jumped right on the boat stating it
> > would be good, please explain what functionality would be added.
> 
> That's not my argument.  I think it sounds like a good idea because I
> think the existing configuration language is ugly, ad-hoc, and
> un-extensible.  As it is, I don't want to touch it.  But I don't have
> a specific wish-list of added functions, just a design sense that the
> existing language is far too impoverished to really capture the
> configuration domain.

Again, I said the same thing two months ago on the users list.  I really
dislike the format of .fvwm2rc (and .fvwmrc, for that matter).  Not in
that they are incapable of doing some impressive things: some of the
configs people have make it clear that with patience modules like
FvwmButtons are amazingly flexibly, including being able to fake the CDE
bar's appearance fairly well.  I dislike them because they are ugly,
rife with +'s and ""'s and other junk.

I won't, however, argue that including an interpreter (again, be it
guile, perl, tcl, python, whetever) in the core is a Good Thing.  It's
certainly a good thing as a module, and modules like FvwmCpp and FvwmM4
show that it's possible to have a module provide config files for the
parent.

It doesn't, however, belong in the core.

> > Not the general code cleanup that has been done and is sorely needed in
> > Fvwm, but the linking of Guile (or, for that matter, requiring any
> > language to be built into the core).
> 
> OK.  You concede that we need "code cleanup".  Why resist embedding
> Guile as a tactic for actually accomplishing this?  There is after all
> evidence (in the form of scwm itself, 6K smaller) that the tactic works.

No there is no such evidence.  I could trim fvwm2 down to a 10k binary
by dynamically loading the other 160k.  Heck, my perl is only 10k by
that logic, since it uses a dynamic library.  The real footprint is
going to include libguile, as I have no other programs that I use that
require it: the disk space and RAM will not be shared by anything.

'Conceding' a code cleanup is needed is nothing new: it's been known for
years.

> Nope.  I'd probably make Guile and filtering a build-time option.  Not
> because I'd fear a fork, but simply for parsimony's sake.

So why not in this case?  It's trivial to #ifdef things.  Until the
Great Style Rewrite, lots of things in fvwm2 will be ifdef'd.  That's
not what's being argued for, though.

What's being asked is not parsimony, it's assimilation.  "We want to
call scwm 'fvwm3' and will require linking an interpreter into your core
WM."

It's not "we have cleaned up the core a lot, and even fixed the weird
2-space indents in places, want to merge the cleaned up code back into
the core".  It drags along a hefty price tag in memory, execution and
disk space that you keep ignoring.

> > And a WM isn't that complicated.  Some very respectible WM's exist that
> > have no such language.  WindowMaker, AfterStep, Enlightenment -- none of
> > which require such a language.
> 
> And, IIRC, all of these are "one-true-way" WMs designed to enforce a
> single theory of interface-gesture design.  Not analogous to fvwm2 at
> all.

Not really, unless you restrict yourself to configuration via menus.
With AfterStep, the scattered remains of .fvwm2rc are even clearly
evident (just scattered amongst piles of directories).  It will still do
most of the fvwm2 things (of a year or so ago, anyway, before their
fork) I've tried, it's just a pain in the rear end to edit a million
files and create files with the name I want appearing in the menu.
As I said, AfterStep is still close enough to Fvwm2 that 'Wharf' works
fine and dandy and is buried the extras directory.  My main objection is
their new-improved-scatter-the-rc code.

Enlightenment is about as far from 'one-true-way' as you can get, in
fact.

> > So precisely, why should I accept more complexity in the program
> > (certainly adding an interpreter is going to add complexity) instead of
> > just cleaning up the existing code?
> 
> I think your premise is wrong and Greg Badros is clearly right about
> this issue, if perhaps vulnerable on others.  Embedding Guile will actually
> *lower* total complexity by banishing the nasty ad-hoc code that gives
> rise to so much of it.

I still disbelieve that: when I look at the code, I see that Greg has
done a fine job in cleaning up the patch-after-patch-after-patch that
fvwm2 is.  I don't see the gain from being the linking of Guile.
Perhaps the linking was the motivation, but that's not WHY his code is
cleaner.  If all the guile hooks were removed (or #ifdef'd), the code
would be no more messy except perhaps for the scattered ifdef's.

> Yesterday I believed this on general design-engineering grounds.  Today
> I believe it because I've dipped into the code and configs enough to
> see that it's specifically true of scwm.

Are you confusing the "Greg has done a massive cleanup" advantage with
linking in Guile?  The code to interpret configs is not that large a
part of fvwm (we'd have a more readable config format if it was).

> You aren't going to win the total-complexity argument, because you're
> simply wrong there.  You might win the big-footprint, compatibility,
> or stability arguments.  I suggest you focus on those.

All I see is that he has cleaned up the code well.  That is good: but
that doesn't answer whether embedding a language is good.  They are
seperate issues.

Again, for total complexity, you need to include libguile.  You seem to
keep forgetting that it's not a dl-stub, but a genuine library larger
than the code it is being linked to.  Does it really add no complexity
to a program to add an interpreted language?  Then, what the heck, let's
link in libperl, and tcl and python as well: why stop with one, when it
will be no more complex?

Or is your math off?

