On Thu, Jul 16, 1998 at 10:49:54PM -0400, Eric S. Raymond wrote:
> OK, then -- how would you feel about a design that used Guile to interpret
> configs and then threw Guile away?  Would that count as being "in the core"?

Would guile be mandatory, or could I preprocess them by hand (or with
another module, or cpp, m4 or even awk?).  If FvwmGuile was akin to
FvwmM4, I'd have no problem with it: it would be purely optional.
I mentiond something similar back in May.  I'd love for menus to be
written something like:

Applications {
     "The Scrape"   =>  /usr/local/bin/netscape,
     "Workman"      =>  /usr/openwin/bin/workman,
etc, with flags and icons and such shoved in in a similar style...
sorta perlish, not really, though, and as long as it wasn't laden
with "" and "+" and "I" and other magic incantations that fvwm2 has,
it would be a Good Thing.

> > No there is no such evidence.  I could trim fvwm2 down to a 10k binary
> > by dynamically loading the other 160k.
> 
> Wouldn't accomplish anything, as you correctly point out.  Moving a lot
> of the complexity into Guile is a different case -- because the complexity
> cost of Guile is somebody *else's* problem, specifically one for the clever 
> specialists on the Guile team.  And one of the underappreciated benefits
> of code re-use is that when lots of projects depend on a common facility
> like Guile, it tends to improve much more rapidly than ad-hoc code would.

But that complexity adds a layer of confusion.  Try working with a
project like perl's Mail::Cclient.... are problems because of my code,
perl, the modules, or c-client (especially when the developer is working
with a -dev release of perl and I have to use a production version)? 
Or PHP's imap.so, again, using c-client.  Are problems in PHP,
imap.so, or c-client.  (Can you tell I'm playing with IMAP a lot
lately?)

Finger-pointing isn't fun.  (I'm sure Tom Dickey likes that he can
reconcile (vile|lynx)/xterm/ncurses strangeness himself, since he
controls both projects.)   Building projects around -dev code isn't fun.

-dev window managers are dangerous beasts considering the WM's role in
things.

> > So why not in this case?  It's trivial to #ifdef things.  Until the
> > Great Style Rewrite, lots of things in fvwm2 will be ifdef'd.  That's
> > not what's being argued for, though.
> 
> I certainly wouldn't be opposed to having "stock" fvwm2 and scwm generated
> from the same source base, if that turned out to be possible and that's
> what you mean.

That's exactly what I meant and what I have said for two months.  I'd
even like to see things like more stuff moved into libfvwm and libfvwm
made into a shared library, since there is a lot of duplicated code in
some of the modules (like IconMan has a pile of stuff that is in core:
those who use only core would pay a small cost to move the contents of
icons.c into libfvwm.so and the there would be a savings in IconMan to
share (both on disk and in RAM) the same library.

The current .a file only makes for 'convenience' functions without any
real benefit to the user and still there is tons of duplicated code
in the tree.

> > Enlightenment is about as far from 'one-true-way' as you can get, in
> > fact.
> 
> Visually, maybe.  Not logically or gesturally, which is the key point.

It's not about piles of optional extensions, no.  But, then, neither is
a mandatory and very large extension.

> > All I see is that he has cleaned up the code well.  That is good: but
> > that doesn't answer whether embedding a language is good.  They are
> > seperate issues.
> 
> Greg doesn't think they're separate.  And since he co-implemented, and
> I understand in a general software-engineering way how he might be
> right, I'm inclined to believe him

He's right in that it was the motivator for cleaning the code.  If the
code wasn't so wierd (2-space tabs at the start of lines, 4 or 8
elsewhere, depending on mood, huge functions that extend for pages that
look awful similar to other functions, macros for skipping white space
in a config file instead of functions, etc) and he didn't want to
implement a lot of changes, he wouldn't have needed the rewrite.

The same general code cleanup is a major reason The Great Style Rewrite
hasn't happened, despite years of knowing it was needed (and tons of
features being left out for lack of bits).  If someone wrote a
way-cool-new-style-flag and was as motivated to get it in as Greg was to
get Guile in, then they would spend the time to clean up the code.

I think scwm was the kick in the pants to make him say "ugh, I need to
clean this mess up before I can do anything with it", not that by
linking in guile the code magically cleaned itself.

Were it that easy, then the Great Style Rewrite would be done and we'd
have clean code.

