brian moore <bem@cmc.net> writes:

> Would guile be mandatory, or could I preprocess them by hand (or with
> another module, or cpp, m4 or even awk?).  If FvwmGuile was akin to
> FvwmM4, I'd have no problem with it: it would be purely optional.

Not in SCWM (that's not to say that it couldn't be done that way, but
that's not how things work for us).  In particular, primitives in scwm
are more truly primitives.  Scheme code then builds on top of the
primitives useful functionality that fvwm2 had as primitives.  e.g., the 
window list code is a Scheme procedure in SCWM, but was a native C
primitive in fvwm2.  The advantage:  The end user can customize
virtually anything about the window list w/o mucking with the C code.
fvwm2 is #ifdef-fed to death.  We use very few ifdefs in SCWM, and then
only in reasonably structured ways. 

<snip>
> > specialists on the Guile team.  And one of the underappreciated benefits
> > of code re-use is that when lots of projects depend on a common facility
> > like Guile, it tends to improve much more rapidly than ad-hoc code would.
> 
> But that complexity adds a layer of confusion.  Try working with a

This is certainly true.  Building SCWM has an extra dependence that
fvwm2 doesn't have, but in general the stable releases build cleanly and 
are configure based (this only recently happened to fvwm2 and still
isn't mainstream I believe).

Debugging SCWM can be harder, but things will get better as Guile
becomes more stable.  Evolving with an evolving language has its
down-sides, but the guile folks are great, and development is active, so 
we know it's well worth our while.

<snip>

> I think scwm was the kick in the pants to make him say "ugh, I need to
> clean this mess up before I can do anything with it", not that by
> linking in guile the code magically cleaned itself.

It really did work *both* ways.  The cleanup that guile gave us for free 
was more closely observed by Maciej, as he did the original embedding of 
guile.  One simple example of how guile simplified a *lot* of code was
in the arguments to the primitives.  fvwm2 primitives each parse their
own arguments, sometimes using one of a bunch of somewhat standard
functions, sometimes in completely ad-hoc ways.  This makes the
configuration language far less uniform and understandable.  All of the
ugliness is take care of for us in SCWM, and our primitives are shorter
and more readable.

Greg
