On 16 Jul 1998, Brady Montz wrote:

> I see three potential directions, each worthy of discussion:
> 
> 1. Return fvwm to its roots, rewrite it, strip it down, and either find a way
>    to move all of the extra functionality people have been grafting on it into
>    modules or just get rid of them. People supporting this will have to make a 
>    case that such a program will survive, stay supported, and not disappear
>    and strand its users.

This option sounds good to me.  As everyone has observed: there is far too
much crud in the current sources. 

There were a couple of reasonable posts in the last 24 hours or so
advocating a cleaned-up core (preferrably in a shareable object) and
shoving all the "configuration" or "command" functionality into a second
layer built on top of the core. 

To my mind, it would be great if fvwm2 and scwm shared the same core.  I
can imagine having in the future, an fvwm2 binary linked to libfvwm, and
having an scwm binary linked to the *same* libfvwm, as well as to
libguile. 

Since the scwm folks have already gone through a "crud-reducing" phase
with fvwm sources, it would be nice to harness their expertise while doing
the same with the current fvwm sources.  There was one claim that they had
gotten the scwm binary down to 2/3 the fvwm2 size by cleaning up the code. 
I suggest that fvwm2 concentrate on the same task.  I realise that some of
the "savings" were derived from pushing the functionality into libguile,
and thus illusory.  Yet, it seems clear to me that there is much to gain
from a careful re-engineering of the sources.

To echo the point that grafting guile into fvwm was an impetus to cleaning
up the code: as I was trying to put the sources under autoconfigure, I had
to look at small bits of the sources.  I found some rather amazing coding
practices, such non-void functions that sometimes didn't return a value! 
(And yet, the return value was used by some of the function's callers)
There are many things that compiling with "gcc -Wall" would point out in a
millisecond.  I fixed the ones that I found, but the changes got lost as
the 2.0.47 versions were not based on the autoconfigured code.

Everyone agrees that scwm & guile are not stable enough for general usage. 
I can't see the gain in radically changing the direction and size of fvwm
to accommodate some alpha-quality interpreter.  I'm not interested in
claims that guile will be "lean and mean" at some unspecified time in the
future.  Such claims have to be viewed skeptically --- not that I doubt
the sincerity of the proponents, but what piece of software *ever* got
smaller? 

I do see gain in building a compact core of wm functions, to be used with
both fvwm2 or scwm.  Moreover, the process of teasing apart the "core" and
"command/configure" layers will be akin to what scwm did.  Hence, a
similar amount of cleanup and bugfixing should occur.

--
