"Eric S. Raymond" <esr@snark.thyrsus.com> wrote:
> I think so, too.  As a person who's not in either the fvwm or scwm camps,
> but who's been around the track a few times, I may have a strategy to suggest
> for accomplishing it.  It'll take a little give and goodwill on both sides.
>
> I can see a merge working given three commitments:
>
> 1. The scwm people must provide a fully capable .fvwm2rc-to-.scwmrc
>    translator.
>
> 2. Scwm must support all existing fvwm2 modules.

We want to do both of these things anyway, although your phrasing it
this way implies a much higher level of priority and a higher degree
of robustness and completeness.

>
> 3. The fvwm people must accept that for the first few releases (until
>    guile gets space-tuned), the scwm/fvwm3 code may have a bigger footprint
>    than the existing fvwm2.  
>
> In other words: if the scwm people will live with a requirement that
> scwm be painlessly upward-compatible with fvwm2, and the fvwm2 people
> will cut them *temporary* slack on the footprint issue, we can all
> make this work.

[included for context, but I can't speak to this directly]

> There's a reason I emphasize `temporary'.  We're talking about replacing
> the ad-hoc config code with Guile.  A key advantage of this is that it
> would allow fvwm to leverage lots more brains than just the fvwm workers.
> Better dynamic-loading and modularization for Guile is critical-path
> for lots of projects besides ours.  It's much more likely that Guile 
> will improve dramatically than that we will ever get motivated enough to
> clean up the ad-hoc cruft in fvwm2's present guts.

I have to agree on this point and strongly emphasize it. Guile is
maintained by a group of people who are really smart about language
design and implementation. There are also a number of projects that
depend on Guile enough that people actively report Guile bugs, send
patches, and make actual improvements to the core that enhance Guile
in numerous ways. 

Furthermore, the Guile developers place a high priority on supporting
apps that use Guile. In particular, they have been very willing to fix
bugs for us and to listen to our feature requests and architectural
suggestions, even when these were things that were important for scwm
but perhaps not crucial for Guile per se. I can only imagine the level
of responsiveness increasing if fvwm and scwm merged, resulting in a
project that both worked the guile core really hard and had a really
high profile.

> Eventually, here's what I hope we can all agree to deliver:  a version of
> scwm that, when called through a link named fvwm2, reads .fvwm2rc,
> translates it on the fly to Guile, and runs just like fvwm2 (modulo
> bug fixes).

Although upward compatibility would obviously be essential, I am
unsure if this specific way of stating it (run through a link called
fvwm2 and get fvwm2 behavior) is necessarily the greatest thing. I say
this not because I don't think it's feasible, but because I think
people who want something that looks acts and feels just like fvwm2
should consider just using fvwm2. There's still a lot of people who
use fvwm1 because it better meets there needs. Of course, it is
possible that a guilified fvwm will be able to do everything fvwm2
does, only better, including the typical use memory footprint. In this
case, a very close emulation mode would be worth cconsidering.


> The program used for .fvwm2rc-to-Guile translation should, of course,
> be available standalone for people who want to go pure Guile right away.

Well, that's the way the initial version will work, at least.

 - Maciej
