I realize that it was intentional, and I accept that in case of a
merge that your phrasing and it's implication are correct. In other
words, I personally accept these burdens. I think Greg will also agree
that these are fair requirements for a merge. My point was just that
these are things we are doing already, and accepting this burden only
means raising the priority relative to other things.


> > Although upward compatibility would obviously be essential, I am
> > unsure if this specific way of stating it (run through a link called
> > fvwm2 and get fvwm2 behavior) is necessarily the greatest thing.
> 
> You have a basic decision to make.  Are you serious about world
> domination?  Do you really want to become the mainstream of fvwm
> development, and capture the fvwm name and associated reputation?
> Then I don't think you can duck, dodge, or temporize away this
> requirement.
> 

Please note that I did not say that it was technically infeasible or
even difficult. In fact, with a comple fvwmrc translator and 100%
compatible module interface (something that did not happen on either
count for the fvwm1 -> fvwm2 scwitch!), both of which I fully accept
need to happen, this is a matter of adding on the order of 10 lines of
C code to check argv[0] and run some special code if it equals
"fvwm2". So I have no desire to dodge this part of the requirement in
the sense of not wanting to put in the work. 

I just question whether on technical grounds, the specific issue of
having an "fvwm2" symlink is technically a good idea (for reasons
stated in my previous message). In fact, I almost decided not to raise
this nitpick for fear of being misconstrued as I seem to have been,
i.e. as ducking the necessity of 100% total backward compatibility.


> So far, you and Greg have been very convincing in arguing the
> increased elegance and flexibility of scwm and the superior
> cleanliness of the scwm code.  You're vulnerable on three other
> issues; stability, footprint, and compatibility.
> 
> My take is that you can get away with handwaving at most one of these.
> If you try to fudge two or more, the fvwm2 community will likely yawn
> and invite you to piss off -- *and be right to do so*.
> 
> You can't nail down the stability issue, not with Guile still in alpha.
> You score at best a draw on footprint, depending on whether your
> audience is willing to consider libguile a `sunk cost' like libc.
> 
> Therefore, you *must* nuke the compatibility problem.  It's the only
> way you have to show the fvwm2 people you're serious about holding
> up your end of a merge.

I agree with all this, except that <nitpick>Guile is not still in
alpha, it is in heavy development between releases, but that is a
different issue.</nitpick>

But, I think it is fair to say about all three of all these issues
that we are working on them, and commit to serious improvement. Scwm
is in a phase of development where, for most of the current users,
adding features, fixing bugs and cleaning up the code are much more
important than backwards compatibility, stability (in the sense of
interfaces not changing as opposed to the sense of few bugs - scwm is
less buggy than some theoretically more mature window managers) or
resource consumption. But as the development cycle progresses, all of
these issues will be afressed on way or another. In case of a merge,
they will all get much higher priority earlier on.

In any case, I am already working on a fvwmrc->scwmrc translator, and
improvements to the fvwm2 module compatibility code are being worked
on by several people, including me. In fact, one person who just sent
me patches expressed the desire to personally enhance the code to be
able to run all exisiting fvwm modules perfectly.

