It sounds to me as though most of the discussion is really concentrated on
a couple of points,

 1. Since to some it sounds like SCWM is the future of where FVWM ought to
    be headed, the SCWM guys (with some FVWM blessing) have been asked to
    come on the mailing list and make their case

 2. The concerns that have been noted are
    a. RAM  memory footprint
    b. disk memory footprint
    c. ease of coding (extensibility)
    d. cleaner interface (primitives)
    e. usefulness ?

Let me first start by saying that I am an avid Fvwm-1/2 user and have been for
the past 3-4 years.  I love Fvwm, but lack the necessary C-skills (and time)
to really delve into the code (alas, I've made suggestions in the past, asked
questions, assisted a few people, etc) -- I keep up by reading the archives on
an almost daily basis.

So I'm your typical user that wants to be involved, but stays in the shadows.

Let me address each point noted above separately (for whatever that's worth)

 1.  I don't have a problem with this point

 2a. Fvwm has _always_ prided itself on having a really small RAM footprint
     (regardless of RAM cost :-) and that is really important to alot of
     people (it usually translates to speed, etc).  The SCWMers have noted
     that Guile is in needed fat as is SCWM code TODAY and that they are
     willing to do their part to slim it down.  Guile is planned to slim
     a bit (I wouldn't hold my breath, but at least the issue is on the
     table).
  b. This really shouldn't be of much concern since we are talking about
     Kbytes that don't amount to much anyway.
  c.
  d. SCWMer have repeatedly expressed that they have a cleaner framework in
     place which certainly leads to cleaner/easier code - I'm not about to
     refute any of this since I haven't delved into the code in any great
     lengths (but what I've seen seems the to be the definition of ad-hoc).
     It sounds as though one will have a greater deal of control of the
     interworking of the WM with a more robust config language (again I
     don't know anything about Guile)
  e. Ah, the clincher !!  Is this at all useful or is it just plain 'old
     COOL to do ?  Now, I haven't really read anyone say anything that made
     me go "wow, that would be nice to do, but damn it Fvwm doesn't allow me
     to do it".  To be open minded, we don't know what we (FVWMer users) are
     missing until we are told that one can do this, that and the other
     (that's when ideas and options seem to abound)

OK, what does this all mean.  From my prospective here's how I look at it,

1. Let's get Fvwm-2.1 OUT
2. Let's have "The Great Style Rewrite" done with
3. Let's restructure the WM into a configuration layer and a core layer
   (per Bob Woodside's <proteus@pcnet.com> suggestion)
4. Let's have the SCWM guys spend more time and effort on memory footprint
5. If scwm's (including Guile) footprint is acceptable AND it mimics _all_ of
   Fvwm functions AND its as fast as FVWM, then I think the decision would
   pretty simple :-)

Again, I might be naive in saying what I said or in over simplifying life, but
that's my take on this.

Questions/Requests:
  + Could an SCWMer post an example of their .scwmrc file (for comparison) ?
  + I'm curious about what SCWM can do today (or in the future) that wouldn't
    be possible under FVWM ?
  + One thing to note is, in what ways will the end-user have to adapt or
    change to start using SCWM (if it were to be fvwm3) ?

 - Nadim
