> 1. Put FvwmAudio back

Okay, finally nailed it.... :)

There's a long standing core-dumping evil bug in FvwmAudio that I
finally nailed with Bounds Checking:

FvwmAudio.c:436:Bounds error: illegal pointer used in pointer arithmetic.

That of course, is bad.

The code (with line numbers)
434             while (1)
435             {
436                 if ((count = read(fd[1],header,
437                                   HEADER_SIZE*sizeof(unsigned long))) <= 0)
438                     done(0);

and the fun one from backtrace:

#5  0x804953c in Loop (fd=0x2074736f) at FvwmAudio.c:436

That's 'ost ' on an Intel bass-ackwards chip: looks like a stack
smashing.

A bit of digging near &fd and I see:
0xbffff6a0 <_serv_stayopen+3086390984>:  "`\013\bNetscape: FAQ: If the
IP address or host name of a name server needs to be changed, do all the
domains and network r"

There's the 'ost ' as part of 'host name'.

So, I dig around a bit more:

(gdb) print &fd
$10 = (int **) 0xbffff734
(gdb) print &body
$11 = (long unsigned int (*)[24]) 0xbffff698

Hrrrm... looks like body is overflowing.  There should be a check in
FvwmAudio (and probably elsewhere) to make sure the reported body_length
is < MAX_BODY_SIZE... but then we'll have to resync somehow, which will
be fun, no doubt.

Or it could get rid of that pesky fixed size buffer that will break on
long names, which is probably the best bet.

It looks like the code in FvwmEvent to discard the body will fail on
this as well: it will require a buffer large enough to hold the longest
window title possible because it keeps changing the offset into body[]
instead of really discarding the data.  Or it should have a patch like
the one below for FvwmAudio...

> Still a bunch of bugs to fix.

Yep.

